  "publishedAt": "2026-04-20T15:38:11-06:00",
  "body": "\u003cp\u003eLast year, my daughter and I (and some other family and friends) did a lot of\ncamping. It was something that was difficult to do while my wife was sick, so it\nfelt like it was a long time coming.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDuring the beginning of my\n\u003ca href=\"https://synic.dev/article/2026-02-11/2025-my-year-of-loss-grief-burnout-and-self-reflection\"\u003eburnout\u003c/a\u003e,\nI started getting this itch to get out somewhere truly alone — somewhere nobody\ncould reach me and I could just sit with my own thoughts for a while. I decided\nI was going to go on a solo backpacking trip. The problem was, it was November,\nand most of our mountain areas were already buried in snow. I also wanted\nsomewhere that would be, in my mind, \u0026quot;solo backpacking training wheels\u0026quot; — so I\npicked \u003ca href=\"https://stateparks.utah.gov/parks/antelope-island/\"\u003eAntelope Island\u003c/a\u003e, a\nlittle island sitting on the East side of the Great Salt Lake. It has some\nmountainous terrain, but it's low enough that snow wasn't an issue yet. It's\nclose to civilization, cell service is spotty but present, and the most\ndangerous thing out there is supposed to be the bison.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI ended up being spectacularly wrong about the \u0026quot;training wheels\u0026quot; part. It was an\nincredible trip and exactly what I needed, but there were a couple of moments\nwhere I genuinely considered hitting the emergency button on my Garmin. As you\ncan see below, I had some unexpected visitors...\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent.webp\" alt=\"Bison by my tent\" loading=\"eager\" decoding=\"sync\" fetchpriority=\"high\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-by-tent.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAntelope Island has a few camping spots, most of them right off the road. But\nthey also have 4 backcountry sites tucked away with a roughly 5 mile approach\nthat you have to reserve ahead of time. I searched everywhere for a map showing\nexactly where the sites were, but the best I could find was a vague circle on\nthe island\u0026#39;s trail map.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI found the trailhead, strapped on my 32lb pack (you have to pack in all your\nwater — there\u0026#39;s no potable source on the island), and set off. About a mile in,\nI spotted another backpacker heading the opposite direction, back toward the\nparking lot.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026#34;Hey, you coming from the backcountry sites?\u0026#34; I called out. \u0026#34;Do you know where\nthey actually are?\u0026#34;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHe shook his head. \u0026#34;I have no idea where they are either. I was going to camp\ntonight, but there\u0026#39;s a herd of bison crossing the trail up ahead and I\u0026#39;ve been\nwaiting for like an hour. I\u0026#39;m done.\u0026#34;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSure enough, I could see them in the distance — a massive herd of bison, slowly\ndrifting across the trail like they had nowhere to be.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail.webp\" alt=\"Bison crossing the trail\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-crossing-trail.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy the time I reached them, it was the tail end of the crossing and I only had\nto wait about half an hour. Looking back, if I had known the trail better and\nwhere the backcountry sites were relative to my position, I might have realized\nwhere that herd was heading...\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAlong the way I passed a few more bison, some elk, and a surprising number of\nmountain bikers. When I finally rounded the massive rock formation to my left\n(called Elephant Rock), the landscape opened up and I could see the mouth of\nSplit Rock Canyon — where the backcountry campsites are tucked away.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon.webp\" alt=\"Split Rock Canyon\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/split-rock-canyon.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI found the fork in the trail that led to the campsite and started setting up.\nWhile I was inflating my sleeping pad, I heard grunting in the distance. Low,\nrumbling sounds echoing off the canyon walls. I looked up and saw the bison herd\n— the same one from earlier — approaching from a completely different direction,\nheading straight for the canyon I was camping in. They were still pretty far\naway, but they were moving with purpose.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHere\u0026#39;s my crudely marked up map. The blue line is the trail I hiked in on. The\ngreen line is the path the bison herd took. It looks like they walked straight\ninto the lake, but unfortunately, the Great Salt Lake has receded so much that\ntheir path is now solid ground.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map.webp\" alt=\"Map of my route and the bison herd\u0026#39;s route\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1221\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/island-map.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy the time I finished with my sleeping pad, the herd was almost on top of me. I\nhad assumed they\u0026#39;d keep going in a straight line and pass right by camp, but I\nwas wrong — they turned, and it happened way faster than I expected. I grabbed a\nfew essentials, zipped up the tent, and scrambled toward the hillside where I\ncould duck behind some rocks if things got dicey. The park website is very\nclear: do not approach the bison, \u003cem\u003eespecially\u003c/em\u003e if there are calves. Well, there\nwere calves. I wasn\u0026#39;t taking any chances.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOne problem, though. In my rush, I left all my water, my warm layers, and — most\ncritically — my Garmin in the tent. All I had was my phone, which thankfully had\njust enough signal to make a call if I really needed to.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo I sat there and waited. I had bolted for the hills around 4:00 in the\nafternoon. The herd didn\u0026#39;t fully clear the campsite until about 5:30. The sun\nwas going down, the temperature was dropping, and I was sitting on a rock in a\nt-shirt watching bison graze next to my tent.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOnce they finally settled into the canyon beyond camp, I crept back, made\ndinner, ate, took some photos, and crawled into my sleeping bag. I could hear\nthe bison all night — grunting, shuffling, occasionally snorting. It was\nimpossible to tell if they were right outside my tent or a mile away.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhen I got up in the morning, sure enough, they were still hanging around in the\ncanyon, but slowly drifting south, away from me.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon.webp\" alt=\"Bison in the canyon in the morning\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/morning-canyon.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe day before, while I was setting up camp, I had noticed a large cliff behind\nme. I could hear voices carrying down from the top — when I looked up, I saw two\npeople sitting on the edge, just taking in the view. On my way out the next\nmorning, I decided to take a detour and check it out for myself. It was a 2.5\nmile side trip off the main trail, so I stashed my pack in a bush and headed up.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI made it almost to the cliff overlook when I came around a bend and found a\nsingle bison sitting directly on the trail. No way around him. He wasn\u0026#39;t moving.\nThat was as far as I got.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"photo lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail.webp\" alt=\"Bison blocking the trail to the cliff\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/bison-on-trail.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI turned around, hiked back down, grabbed my pack, and headed home. All in all,\nit was an amazing trip — stunning scenery, some genuinely tense wildlife\nencounters, and exactly the kind of solitude I needed. I would absolutely do it\nagain. But next time, one lesson learned: if you\u0026#39;re going to bring a Garmin,\nkeep it on your person.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHere\u0026#39;s an album of some more images from the trip:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"album\" role=\"region\" aria-label=\"Image album\" data-album-id=\"album-b-0\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-frame\" style=\"aspect-ratio:1600/1067\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-scroller\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-item\" data-index=\"0\"\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"album-img lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach.webp\" alt=\"The approach trail\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/approach.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-item\" data-index=\"1\"\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"album-img lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp.webp\" alt=\"My campsite\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/camp.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-item\" data-index=\"2\"\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"album-img lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset.webp\" alt=\"Sunset over the island\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/sunset.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-item\" data-index=\"3\"\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"album-img lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog.webp\" alt=\"Morning fog\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/fog.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"album-item\" data-index=\"4\"\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach-md.webp 640w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach-lg.webp 1000w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach.webp 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 75vw\"/\u003e\u003cimg class=\"album-img lightbox-img\" src=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach.webp\" alt=\"Approaching the cliff overlook\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1067\" srcset=\"/static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-trip/cliff-approach-sm.webp 480w, /static/images/articles/2026-04-20_my-first-solo-backpacking-tri